    {
      "id": "oX51cdS4KI98-hkxs5Ara",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1111.5300376093371,
      "y": 214.8903954994118,
      "width": 1437.3552702394707,
      "height": 1096.2,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3E",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1134075746,
      "version": 3401,
      "versionNonce": 1967501470,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1774889718557,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "High Level Design\n\n- The platform has a UI component which helps developers configure the datasources and the pipelines. When\ncreating a pipiline, the developer needs to define the source configuration, the schema definition for the data in\nthe source, the processing logic to be applied to the pipeline (as a SQL query). The sink could be a custom Rest\nAPI that is used to ingest the data into the platform. However, Flink supports multiple sinks natively so, we can\nsupport multiple options here.\nThe pipilines configurations, as well as datasources and schemas will be stored in dedicated SQL tables. The\nschemas table is defined as a separate table so, we can support versioning and keep the history of the various\nschema changes.\n\n- A Flink framework would be leverage in order to process both batch and streaming data at the customer site.\nThe framework will have different custom data sources implemented and it will take a JSON configuration as an\ninput, build the DAG pipeline based on the config, and run it on a Flink cluster or a single Flink node based on the\ncustomer environment\n\n- The Flink job will be running and processing data within the customer environment so, our platform needs a\nway to trigger this job. There are 2 options here. For customers that have SaaS cloud infra, then they can expose a\nRest API that our platform backend service can call, and then this api will be responsible to submit the Flink job.\nSince this communication happens over the public internet, the customer would need to provide a mechanism for\nmachine to machine authentication, like OAuth 2.0 Client Credentials flow . \nFor customers that have devices running on industrial edge, with restricted networks and no open ports, we can\ndefine an API that the device can poll to retreive the config JSON needed to submit and start a Flink job. Since this\ncommunication will happens over the public internet, the device could leverage mTLS as authentication\nmechanism over TCP.\n\n- In terms of monitoring, we need a way to show in the UI the status of each pipeline (running, failed, etc). An\nendpoint can be exposed in our platform so, it can be invoked by the customer to send updates on the status of a\nrunning pipeline",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "High Level Design\n\n- The platform has a UI component which helps developers configure the datasources and the pipelines. When creating a pipiline, the developer needs to define the source configuration, the schema definition for the data in the source, the processing logic to be applied to the pipeline (as a SQL query). The sink could be a custom Rest API that is used to ingest the data into the platform. However, Flink supports multiple sinks natively so, we can support multiple options here.\nThe pipilines configurations, as well as datasources and schemas will be stored in dedicated SQL tables. The schemas table is defined as a separate table so, we can support versioning and keep the history of the various schema changes.\n\n- A Flink framework would be leverage in order to process both batch and streaming data at the customer site. The framework will have different custom data sources implemented and it will take a JSON configuration as an input, build the DAG pipeline based on the config, and run it on a Flink cluster or a single Flink node based on the customer environment\n\n- The Flink job will be running and processing data within the customer environment so, our platform needs a way to trigger this job. There are 2 options here. For customers that have SaaS cloud infra, then they can expose a Rest API that our platform backend service can call, and then this api will be responsible to submit the Flink job. Since this communication happens over the public internet, the customer would need to provide a mechanism for machine to machine authentication, like OAuth 2.0 Client Credentials flow . \nFor customers that have devices running on industrial edge, with restricted networks and no open ports, we can define an API that the device can poll to retreive the config JSON needed to submit and start a Flink job. Since this communication will happens over the public internet, the device could leverage mTLS as authentication mechanism over TCP.\n\n- In terms of monitoring, we need a way to show in the UI the status of each pipeline (running, failed, etc). An endpoint can be exposed in our platform so, it can be invoked by the customer to send updates on the status of a running pipeline",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    }
  ],
